The former governor of the Bank of Spain, jailed  two weeks ago on suspicion of embezzlement, was released Thursday on 110,000  dollars' bond, prison officials.
The suspect, Mariano Rubio, made no comment as he left the Alcala-Meco  prison near Madrid. He must report to police every two weeks.
His is one of a series of corruption cases that have embarrassed socialist  Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez.
The judge that ordered Rubio's release decided on the other hand to  maintain the imprisonment of another embezzlement suspect, Manuel de la  Concha, Rubio's stock broker.
De la Concha is also the former chairman of the Madrid stock exchange.
If convicted the two men face jail sentences of between five and 20 years.
